<li id="cite_note-10"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFOlson2002">Olson, Steve (2002). <i>Mapping Human History</i>. Houghton Mifflin Books. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0618352104" class="internal">ISBN 0618352104</a>.  "Any adaptations produced by evolution are useful only in the present, not in some vaguely defined future. So the vocal anatomy and neural circuits needed for language could not have arisen for something that did not yet exist"</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Mapping+Human+History&amp;rft.aulast=Olson&amp;rft.aufirst=Steve&amp;rft.au=Olson%2C+Steve&amp;rft.date=2002&amp;rft.pub=Houghton+Mifflin+Books&amp;rft.isbn=0618352104&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Origin_of_language"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-ruhlen-11"><b><a href="#cite_ref-ruhlen_11-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFRuhlen1994"><a href="/wiki/Merritt_Ruhlen" title="Merritt Ruhlen">Ruhlen, Merritt</a> (1994). <i>Origin of Language</i>. p.&#160;3. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0471584266" class="internal">ISBN 0471584266</a>.  "Earlier human ancestors, such as <i>Homo habilis</i> and <i>Homo erectus</i>, would likely have possessed less developed forms of language, forms intermediate between the rudimentary communicative systems of, say, chimpanzees and modern human languages"</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Origin+of+Language&amp;rft.aulast=Ruhlen&amp;rft.aufirst=Merritt&amp;rft.au=Ruhlen%2C+Merritt&amp;rft.date=1994&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B3&amp;rft.isbn=0471584266&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Origin_of_language"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-12"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFJungers.2C_William_L._et._al.2003">Jungers, William L. et. al. (August 2003). "<a href="http://www.baa.duke.edu/kay/site/riogallegos/PDFs/j74.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.baa.duke.edu/kay/site/riogallegos/PDFs/j74.pdf" rel="nofollow">Hypoglossal Canal Size in Living Hominoids and the Evolution of Human Speech</a>" (PDF). <i>Human Biology</i> <b>75</b> (4): 473–484. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<span class="neverexpand"><a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1353%2Fhub.2003.0057" class="external text" title="http://dx.doi.org/10.1353%2Fhub.2003.0057" rel="nofollow">10.1353/hub.2003.0057</a></span><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.baa.duke.edu/kay/site/riogallegos/PDFs/j74.pdf" class="external free" title="http://www.baa.duke.edu/kay/site/riogallegos/PDFs/j74.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://www.baa.duke.edu/kay/site/riogallegos/PDFs/j74.pdf</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-09-10</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Hypoglossal+Canal+Size+in+Living+Hominoids+and+the+Evolution+of+Human+Speech&amp;rft.jtitle=Human+Biology&amp;rft.aulast=Jungers%2C+William+L.+et.+al.&amp;rft.au=Jungers%2C+William+L.+et.+al.&amp;rft.date=August+2003&amp;rft.volume=75&amp;rft.issue=4&amp;rft.pages=473%E2%80%93484&amp;rft_id=info:doi/10.1353%2Fhub.2003.0057&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.baa.duke.edu%2Fkay%2Fsite%2Friogallegos%2FPDFs%2Fj74.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Origin_of_language"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-13"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFDeGusta.2C_David_et._al.1999">DeGusta, David et. al. (1999). "<a href="http://www.pubmedcentral.nih.gov/articlerender.fcgi?artid=15600%094" class="external text" title="http://www.pubmedcentral.nih.gov/articlerender.fcgi?artid=15600%094" rel="nofollow">Hypoglossal Canal Size and Hominid Speech</a>". <i>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America</i> <b>96</b> (4): 1800–1804. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<span class="neverexpand"><a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1073%2Fpnas.96.4.1800" class="external text" title="http://dx.doi.org/10.1073%2Fpnas.96.4.1800" rel="nofollow">10.1073/pnas.96.4.1800</a></span>. <a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9990105" class="external" title="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9990105">PMID 9990105</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.pubmedcentral.nih.gov/articlerender.fcgi?artid=15600%094" class="external free" title="http://www.pubmedcentral.nih.gov/articlerender.fcgi?artid=15600%094" rel="nofollow">http://www.pubmedcentral.nih.gov/articlerender.fcgi?artid=15600%094</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-09-10</span>.  "Hypoglossal canal size has previously been used to date the origin of human-like speech capabilities to at least 400,000 years ago and to assign modern human vocal abilities to Neandertals. These conclusions are based on the hypothesis that the size of the hypoglossal canal is indicative of speech capabilities.".</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Hypoglossal+Canal+Size+and+Hominid+Speech&amp;rft.jtitle=Proceedings+of+the+National+Academy+of+Sciences+of+the+United+States+of+America&amp;rft.aulast=DeGusta%2C+David+et.+al.&amp;rft.au=DeGusta%2C+David+et.+al.&amp;rft.date=1999&amp;rft.volume=96&amp;rft.issue=4&amp;rft.pages=1800%E2%80%931804&amp;rft_id=info:doi/10.1073%2Fpnas.96.4.1800&amp;rft_id=info:pmid/9990105&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.pubmedcentral.nih.gov%2Farticlerender.fcgi%3Fartid%3D15600%25094&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Origin_of_language"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-constrainingtime-14"><b><a href="#cite_ref-constrainingtime_14-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFJohansson.2C_Sverker2006">Johansson, Sverker (April 2006). "<a href="http://www.tech.plymouth.ac.uk/socce/evolang6/johansson_constraining.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.tech.plymouth.ac.uk/socce/evolang6/johansson_constraining.pdf" rel="nofollow">Constraining the Time When Language Evolved</a>" (PDF). <i>Evolution of Language: Sixth International Conference, Rome</i>: 152. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<span class="neverexpand"><a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1142%2F9789812774262_0020" class="external text" title="http://dx.doi.org/10.1142%2F9789812774262_0020" rel="nofollow">10.1142/9789812774262_0020</a></span><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.tech.plymouth.ac.uk/socce/evolang6/johansson_constraining.pdf" class="external free" title="http://www.tech.plymouth.ac.uk/socce/evolang6/johansson_constraining.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://www.tech.plymouth.ac.uk/socce/evolang6/johansson_constraining.pdf</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-09-10</span>.  "Hyoid bones are very rare as fossils, as they are not attached to the rest of the skeleton, but one Neanderthal hyoid has been found (Arensburg et al., 1989), very similar to the hyoid of modern Homo sapiens, leading to the conclusion that Neanderthals had a vocal tract similar to ours (Houghton, 1993; Bo¨e, Maeda, &amp; Heim, 1999).".</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Constraining+the+Time+When+Language+Evolved&amp;rft.jtitle=Evolution+of+Language%3A+Sixth+International+Conference%2C+Rome&amp;rft.aulast=Johansson%2C+Sverker&amp;rft.au=Johansson%2C+Sverker&amp;rft.date=April+2006&amp;rft.pages=152&amp;rft_id=info:doi/10.1142%2F9789812774262_0020&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.tech.plymouth.ac.uk%2Fsocce%2Fevolang6%2Fjohansson_constraining.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Origin_of_language"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
